**Task: Building a React Component with TypeScript for a Dashboard**

### Step 1: Set up the Project Structure

To start, we need to create a new React project with TypeScript. We can use the `create-react-app` command with the `--template typescript` flag to set up the project.

```bash
npx create-react-app dashboard --template typescript
```

### Step 2: Install Required Dependencies

We'll need to install the following dependencies:

* `@types/react`: TypeScript definitions for React
* `@types/react-dom`: TypeScript definitions for React DOM
* `react-router-dom`: For client-side routing
* `axios`: For making API requests

```bash
npm install @types/react @types/react-dom react-router-dom axios
```

### Step 3: Create the Dashboard Component

Create a new file called `Dashboard.tsx` in the `src` directory. This will be our main dashboard component.

```typescript
// src/Dashboard.tsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { Link, Route, Switch } from 'react-router-dom';
import axios from 'axios';

interface DashboardProps {
  // Add props if needed
}

const Dashboard: React.FC<DashboardProps> = () => {
  const [data, setData] = useState<any[]>([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchData = async () => {
      setLoading(true);
      try {
        const response = await axios.get('https://api.example.com/data');
        setData(response.data);
      } catch (error) {
        setError(error);
      } finally {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    };
    fetchData();
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Dashboard</h1>
      {loading ? (
        <p>Loading...</p>
      ) : error ? (
        <p>Error: {error.message}</p>
      ) : (
        <ul>
          {data.map((item) => (
            <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};

export default Dashboard;
```

### Step 4: Create the App Component

Update the `App.tsx` file to include the `Dashboard` component.

```typescript
// src/App.tsx
import React from 'react';
import { BrowserRouter, Route, Switch } from 'react-router-dom';
import Dashboard from './Dashboard';

function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <Switch>
        <Route path="/" component={Dashboard} exact />
      </Switch>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}

export default App;
```

### Step 5: Add Routing

We'll add a simple routing system to our app. Create a new file called `routes.ts` in the `src` directory.

```typescript
// src/routes.ts
import { Route, Switch } from 'react-router-dom';
import Dashboard from './Dashboard';

const routes = (
  <Switch>
    <Route path="/" component={Dashboard} exact />
  </Switch>
);

export default routes;
```

### Step 6: Update the Index File

Finally, update the `index.tsx` file to render the `App` component.

```typescript
// src/index.tsx
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom';
import App from './App';

ReactDOM.render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <App />
  </React.StrictMode>,
  document.getElementById('root')
);
```

### Example Use Case

To use this dashboard component, simply navigate to the root URL of your app. The component will fetch data from the API and display it in a list.

### API Documentation

To use the API, send a GET request to `https://api.example.com/data`. The response will be an array of objects with `id` and `name` properties.

### Conclusion

We've successfully built a React component with TypeScript for a dashboard. This component fetches data from an API and displays it in a list. We've also set up a simple routing system using `react-router-dom`. This is a basic example, and you can customize it to fit your needs.

